<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-02-21T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-02-21T15:00:00-05:00" n="459" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d459">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/2244</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-02-21T20:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">February 21, 1916, 8 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>3833. I hear indirectly that the British and French answer to our
                                long shipping note of November 7<note n="3" xml:id="d459fn3">Should
                                    be November 5, date on which the note of October 21 was
                                    delivered in London. See <ref target="frus1915Supp#pg_578">
                                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1915, Supplement,
                                        pp. 578</ref>–<ref target="frus1915Supp#pg_601">601</ref>.</note> will contain an expression of willingness
                                after the war to submit to some international tribunal the validity
                                under international law of the order in council of March 11 and to
                                pay damages if the decision is adverse to the British position. I
                                cannot verify this report but I think it is probably true.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>